","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1497":"1497","1420":"1420","25 October 1410":"25 October 1410","about 1376":"about 1376","28 August 1383":"28 August 1383","1418":"1418","before 1 July 1412":"before 1 July 1412","England":"England","Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England","London, England":"London, England","Combe Raleigh, Devon, England":"Combe Raleigh, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","House of the Carmelite Friars, London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"St","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Southern French: variant of   St  .   Romain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Romain","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Alain, Altagrace, Aurore, Camille, Dominique, Edele, Georges, Henri, Jacques, Jean-Marie, Jean-Michel, Jeanmarie.","French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and English: variant of   Roman  ."]}]},{"name":"Aubyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Andre, Normand, Armand, Cecile, Emile, Henri, Monique, Adelard, Aime, Alcid, Aldege.","French: from the personal name <i>Aubin</i> (from Latin <i>Albinus</i>, a derivative of <i>albus</i> ‘white’). This was the name of several minor early Christian saints, including a famous bishop of Angers (died <i>c.</i> 554). At an early date, this name became confused with the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Albuin</i> (see   Albin  ). Compare   Obey   and   Obin  .","English: variant of   Albin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Albin","meanings":["English, French, and German: from the personal name <i>Albin</i> (from Latin <i>Albinus</i>, a derivative of <i>albus</i> ‘white’). In England this is generally a variant of   Alban  . The usual spelling of the French name is   Aubin  . The personal name was especially popular in Austria, Lombardy, and Savoy, where it absorbed the ancient Germanic name <i>Albuin</i> (which is composed of the elements <i>alb</i> ‘elf’ + <i>win</i> ‘friend’; compare   Alvin  ). This was the name of the Lombard leader (died 572) who made himself king of northern Italy, and also of various Christian saints, including a bishop of Brixen (Bressanone) in South Tyrol.","Galician (<b>Albín</b>): habitational name from any of the four places called Albín in Galicia (Spain), from Latin <i>(villa) Albini</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":5,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John St Aubyn was born in 1377, in Devon, England, his father, Sir John St Aubyn, was 26 and his mother, Joan Chudleigh, was 23. He married Catherine Challons before 1 July 1412. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died on 14 October 1418, in England, at the age of 41, and was buried in London, Middlesex, England."},"et":{"1377–14 October 1418":"1377–14. oktoober 1418","1377–1418":"1377–1418","1384–1420":"1384–1420","1410–Female":"1410–Surnud","1415–1497":"1415–1497","1352–1383":"1352–1383","1355–1423":"1355–1423","1352":"1352","14 October 1418":"14. oktoober 1418","1384":"1384","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1415":"1415","1423":"1423","1377":"1377","1355":"1355","1410":"1410","1497":"1497","1420":"1420","25 October 1410":"25. oktoober 1410","about 1376":"umbes 1376","28 August 1383":"28. august 1383","1418":"1418","before 1 July 1412":"enne 1. juulit 1412","England"